Rainbow Trout living in streams generally have more access to insects and other aquatic invertebrates than those living in still water environments like lakes and ponds. Therefore, it's likely that Rainbow Trout subspecies living in stream environments might consume a higher proportion of insects and other invertebrates in their diet compared to those living in lentic (still water) environments. However, it's important to note that Rainbow Trout are opportunistic feeders and will consume whatever prey is most readily available to them, so the specific proportions of different prey items in their diet can vary depending on a range of ecological factors.
